{
  "text": "Though we continue to pursue these theoretical issues experimentally, the present study represents an extension of this basic memory enhancement methodology to the target population of individuals with mental retardation. This type of structural manipulation of the encoding context may be especially useful for individuals with mental retardation because they often do not spontaneously utilize memory-enhancing encoding strategies. Typically, individuals with mental retardation require explicit instructions and/or prompts to use a specific type of strategy. The present methodology does not involve explicit verbal instructions, strategy training, or prompting of any sort. Rather, the very nature of the presentation format itself induces generation of potential labels for the to-be-identified items. In addition, we expect that the effectiveness of this manipulation is dependent upon the development of an extensive semantic network that likely is experientially based. For example, [CITATION_1] showed that use of a category cue did not facilitate free recall in young children without mental retardation until the age of 8, and children with mental retardation until age 13. They proposed that this finding reflected development of a sophisticated semantic network, and that with age ''there is an increase in the number and richness of automatically elicited associations to a given stimulus'' (p. 29). The inclusion of both chronological age (CA) and mental age (MA) matched groups in the present study allowed us to address this issue directly. If the effect is experientially based, then we would expect that the magnitude of the effect would be greater in the CAmatched and mentally retarded groups than in the MA-matched group.",
  "citation_candidates": [
